As Wittgenstein says, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this 'something,' this je ne sais quoi, that gives art and morality their most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics is their connection point.

I believe that morality and art are closely related because we experience both most intensely at a noumenal level, to use a Kantian term. They affect us at a level that can be experienced but not fully explained. This link is even stronger in literature. As McKean says, "What most distinguishes literature from other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, such as music, but they seem as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values... Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Today's Germany is a formidable power, a united nation with a unique culture that permeates from the shadows of the Alps in Munich to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. This cultural essence can be felt from Cologne on the Rhine river, through the heart of Germany, to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. Given its diverse cultural heritage, it is no surprise that Germany, as we know it today, is a blend of various sources and tribes.

Germania, the ancestral land of the Germans, has a name whose origins are highly debated among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed it came from the Germanic tribe known as the Tungrians, who were previously called Germans before crossing the Rhine and fighting the Gallic forces. Julius Caesar first used the term "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he defeated the Gauls and battled Germanic tribes that often crossed the Rhine. He adopted this term from the Gauls to distinguish between those they had conquered and those they had not. The origin of the name is uncertain; it may come from the spear used by the Germans in warfare, known as a "ger" (O.E.D., 2010), or from the Old Irish word "garim," meaning "to shout," indicating the Germans were loud or noisy.

The Roman historian Tacitus, in his AD 98 work "De Origine et situ Germanorum," described the Germans as aboriginal, not mixed with other races due to immigration or intercourse. He wrote, "I should regard (the Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive....Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were their home?" (Tacitus, 98)

Who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and occasionally lead land campaigns, but mostly returned to their sprawling empire. As Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire, trading their goods and skills by serving in the Roman army (Ozment, 2005, p. 17).

I looked down at the scene in front of me, my mind blankly comprehending the view. Unemotionally, silently, with a practiced awareness that studied but refused to relate the object of study to any abstract understanding, my mind analyzed the picture before my eyes. Thoughts slipped into my mind and slipped out again almost faster than they appeared. So smoothly and so cleanly my consciousness worked that it seemed I had no real thoughts of my own, just an active and liquid experience of what I was looking at.
Once, on advice from an artist I worked with, I purchased an art instruction book called The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain. I had wanted to learn how to draw ever since I was six years old and this book teaches everything from understanding what a pencil is to processes the brain uses to interpret lines. One technique the book teaches is to place a square frame around any picture the artist wishes to study. Thus transforming an overwhelmingly detailed picture, for instance a bowl of fruit sitting on a table located in a kitchen that is connected to a dining room, into an easily grasped picture, that bowl of fruit sitting on a simple plane.
At the time, staring down at the bowl in front of me I could not mentally project that artist’s frame. I was so overwhelmed, so awed that I could only stand and gaze in wonderment. Picasso went through his blue phase, Monet loved greenery, Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of casting my perspective as worthy of the title Artistic then before me were the beginnings of my picture, the start of my story, Work in Brown.
Fingertips alighted on my chosen implement of artistry, muscles tightened and relaxed as my hand passed through space, my mind’s will given shape and form in what could have been the most creative moment of my life. Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean. Flakes of matter broke away from the whole and were carried away to nothingness. Muscles tightening, jerking and spasming a little more quickly and anxiously the second time, my hand smacked the handle of the toilet again. The offensive brown package refused to move, stuck like a slug on the bottom of the toilet.
Mop gripped loosely in hand, feet set a foot apart, green tie knotted uncomfortably around my throat, I frowned slightly as I stared at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter someone had left as a message for the suckers who cleaned the bathrooms at Rite Aid. A few flushes more, a few more tranquil introspective moments to myself, then my hand moved towards the wall to my right, gripped the sheet at the end of the toilet paper, and began mummifying itself until it resembled an oven mitt. Standing up straight, then bending at the waist, my hand dipped slowly into the bowl, like a mother going into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey….

Teenagers are dying in car crashes. Several factors converge to create this deadly trend among the youngest American drivers. The National Institutes of Health point out that one aspect of the issue is that the teenage brain is simply not ready to handle the risks of driving. Lack of experience also plays a significant role. This inexperience not only leads to more fatal accidents but also increases the likelihood of rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road. Teens also fare much worse when traveling with peers, which is something anyone with common sense knows happens frequently. A study by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center found a clear correlation between the age of the passenger and the number of traffic accidents. California and other states have attempted to increase teen driver safety by implementing temporary provisional licenses that restrict driving hours and prohibit other minors as passengers. However, these provisional licenses are merely temporary solutions. The fundamental problem is that, as a group, the youngest drivers are statistically unprepared to handle the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes even 18 is too young for a regular driver's license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman's research suggests a common desire among those under 19-20 to engage in risky behavior for the thrill. Therefore, it makes sense to delay driving until this tendency to seek thrills begins to subside. If we continue to issue driver's licenses to young teens, we will likely see more deadly accidents, and the death toll could become alarming in the next few years. By 2010, the baby boomers' children will be eligible to drive, and millions of new teen drivers will be ready to hit the road. Legislation addressing this issue could be relatively simple. Schools could continue to provide driver's education classes to start the learning process, but no one under the age of 18 should be allowed to drive a vehicle. A provisional permit could still be issued before granting a full driver's license, with a certain number of practical driving hours required, similar to the number already required by the majority of states. A uniform, national law on this issue would be a reasonable and, I believe, effective way to protect teens across the country. This suggested legislation is not a new or untested idea.

In browsing through the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I decided to watch all of the trick films, amounting to fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films primarily utilize creative editing to create illusions. My film analysis generally focuses on describing the poetics of most trick films and examining the unique characteristics of a few later films. Most trick films from the turn of the century are set-bound, composed within a frontal proscenium, feature no camera movement, use long and medium shots, and adhere to the one shot equals one film method. However, some films from the early 20th century challenge these guidelines by introducing elements such as multiple shots.
One common aspect among trick films is their filming within an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move to follow figures or objects from its proscenium position. This composition was prevalent in early films, drawing inspiration from the theatre and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. One limitation of this stage-based style is that figures in trick films typically only move side-to-side and do not walk towards or away from the camera. For instance, in the film "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" (1900), actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even when they exit the frame, the camera does not follow them.
The frontal proscenium composition style also means that shots are usually long shots, and occasionally medium shots. Close-ups are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog. This is reminiscent of the theatre and vaudeville tradition, where the audience sees the entire performance at once, framed by the stage borders. As in most early films, actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups do not occur.
Most early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to around a minute or less, depending on the frames per second. It also restricts the dramatic or narrative use of trick films; most focus on short vaudeville-style tricks like magic, disappearing acts, and switching acts with minimal story. Note that in a trick film, one conceptual shot is not the same as one physical shot. A single “shot” may actually consist of several joined together to create the illusion of apparition or disappearance. Carefully examine "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A closer look reveals the moment when the physical shot with Mary's severed "head" begins, even though the film appears as a single conceptual shot to the viewer.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and ardent proponent of Republicanism. Although he was primarily an agriculturalist, his career in politics and his dedication to his profession made him known for his commitment and outspokenness on issues of personal freedom and governance. His commitment to an agrarian system was the foundation for almost all of his views on government. He saw it as his mission to preserve and encourage what he considered the most superior of all careers, which influenced his arguments on sovereignty, constitutionalism, and even the judicial system. John Taylor believed that the United States had a great opportunity to establish an ideal system, as there was no native tradition to hinder the framers of the government, allowing for the formation of a system of self-government. He strongly believed in the natural rights of man and the interdependence of these rights, meaning that if one is denied, then all will fail, and the value of the remaining ones is diminished. These rights should, therefore, be beyond the reach of the government. He claimed that what some called the "state of nature" meant that those with physical prowess and malevolent intelligence were the ones who benefited, but that in civilization, this should not be the case. In order to create this ideal society, Taylor believed that a government should be established that considers the inherent good and evil within man. Taylor held very rigid views on a dualistic morality, claiming that "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). He defined good principles as those that protect private property, improve agriculture, and discourage capitalism, and believed that a government founded on good principles would function equitably regardless of its administration, which was inevitably led by avarice and self-interest. Self-interest, he believed, was man's motivation in all things, but that it was only considered evil when it led beyond the creation of a society based on the public good to sub-societies that lived at the expense of others. A good government was necessary to retain man's natural evil, and even then it must be under careful observation to prevent the addition of bad principles. Taylor, like many other staunch Republicans of his time, called for a strict construction of the Constitution. He wanted an extremely limited federal government, with no more rights or powers allowed to it than were explicitly stated in the Constitution. He knew that an extensive federal government was expensive, and therefore likely to be despotic. However, he believed that a simple, literal interpretation was dangerous, and that without reference to the intent of the writers, such a method could easily become corrupt. Even more, he considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, because it more explicitly describes the country as a group of sovereign states rather than one nation.

Referring back to Figure 17, there was a sharp decline in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. This was somewhat discouraging, and the reasons behind it are unclear. The onset of winter in a New England campus likely contributed to a decrease in bicycle and foot commuting, which may have accounted for some of the drop. December also marks the end of the fall semester, when everyone is busy wrapping up schoolwork and processing grades, possibly causing the commuter log to fall off the radar. Additionally, December brings the holiday season and a month-long break for students and faculty, during which many do not need to come to campus. Classes resume for the spring semester in late January, which might also explain the low number of logs for that month. However, this does not explain the low number of submissions for February. One might also hypothesize that any project of this nature experiences an initial surge of enthusiasm and energy, which naturally fades over time. To counteract this trend, we introduced the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a special campaign designed to revitalize the initiative, which resulted in an increase in log submissions for that month. Thus, one of the challenges we faced was maintaining project momentum despite the natural decline in engagement and the specific issue of holiday and semester breaks common in higher education. Another challenge for this project, or any alternative commuting project, is the inherent preference people have for driving cars, which is deeply ingrained in our culture. Therefore, it's essential to offer incentives for engaging in alternative modes of commuting. We provided numerous prizes, such as gift cards to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, an independent bookstore, and even some larger national chain stores. It would have been interesting to see the impact of larger prizes, such as giving away a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car, in boosting participation. This could have also helped to combat the dip in engagement the project experienced. The nature of the prizes did not change throughout the project. If the prizes had increased in value over time, this might have helped. The gift cards seemed sufficient at the project's start, but if we had announced additional bicycles in December, and a hybrid or electric car in January, participation and engagement could have increased instead of decreasing.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a type of security that tracks an index, commodity, or a basket of assets, similar to an index fund, but with more flexibility and trades like a stock on an exchange. An ETF offers the diversification of an index fund and the benefits of single stock ownership, such as the ability to short sell, buy on margin, and purchase as few as one share in any transaction. These benefits are highly appealing, but ETFs have lower expense ratios compared to the average mutual fund. However, there is a downside: you must pay a commission on every ETF trade, similar to stock orders. Another advantage of ETFs is the wide variety of funds available. While these benefits are clear, it's always a good idea for savvy financial investors to assess whether these benefits, such as diversification, actually exist and to what extent. For this analysis, we will examine the ETF IHF and compare it against its top 10 holdings to determine if owning a single ETF approximates the benefits of owning a diversified portfolio of the top 10 stocks and whether there are better configurations of these stocks that could offer a more optimal Sharpe ratio or return.

To evaluate the ETF, it would be impractical to include every holding, so we decided to focus on the top 10 holdings, which account for 63.58% of all the assets in the ETF. Below are the top 10 holdings and their percentage of total assets.

To estimate how well these 10 stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can use the current percentage of assets, normalized to 100%, to calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolio's Beta and Return if the portfolio consisted of these 10 stocks in the proportion established by the ETF's holdings. The calculations of Beta and return are shown in the chart below.

From the chart, it is clear that a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings has a return 6.11% higher than the ETF, representing a 16% increase in returns. Additionally, the Beta of the top 10 holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF as a whole. Based on these results, a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could potentially provide a higher return with lower Beta. However, there is a possibility that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different.

To determine if these portfolios are statistically different, we calculated the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalized it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

اشربنالاشعار في "سنّام" من ادجار آلان بو هو أحد أفضل شعراته. في "سنّام" بو يستخدم миллиث "ثولي" في السطور 6 و 56، والذي يرجعه المعبوت إلى فيرجيل. استخدم فيرجيل هذا المصطلح في إشارة إلى جزيرة شمال بريطانيا التي كانت تعتبر حدود العالم المعروف باليونانيين. من المؤكد أن فيرجيل استخدم هذا المصطلح، ولكن هناك مصدر أكثر تحديثًا يجب أن يعطى له بعضCredit. كانت لهبه بو اهتمام كبير في الأدباء الألمان.

هذا الاقتباس مهم لأنه يكشف عن معرفة بو بالعملاء جوتفريد. في كتاب "بو פולيتان و جوتفريد ميجون" يركل كارل أرندت على تشابه قصيدتين من بو وجوتفريد ويصل إلى الخاتمة أنه بو كان يماثل جوتفريد.

يقول دّووكس الإبداعي إلى الأدب الانجليزي عن جوتفريد: "كان جوتفريد كاتبًا مشهورًا للدراما الشعرية "فاوتس" التي نشرها في اثنتي عشرة جزءًا، الأول في 1808 والمكث في العام 1832، عام وفاة جوتفريد. في componeنث lending من "فاوتس" الثاني يحتوي على قصيدة قصيرة بعنوان "الملك من ثولي". قصيدة عن ملك فقد زوجته بعد أن قدم له كوبًا كهدية. بعد وفاة زوجته commence أن يشرب كثيرًا ويبكي من ذكرى زوجته الميتة. ثم يقرر أن الوقت قد حان له أن يموت وإعطاء كل ممتلكاته لابنيه إلا الكوب. ثم يسير إلى صخرة، يرمي الكوب في البحر، يغلق عينيه، ويضطرب. عاطفة الملك من ثولي وصف الملك في "سنّام" ما هو إلا شخصية شبحية لفتاة بو وواجب تشرب. كانت "فاوتس" أيضًا تُنظم إلى دراما رومانسية من قبل ه ب جرايتن في 1842، والتي كانت أقل من عام واحد قبل استخدام بو لمصطلح "ثولي" في "البئر والعبارة".

يستشهد بو الثولي مرتين في مؤلفاته. مرة واحدة في "البئر والعبارة" ولكن استخدامه هذا التعبير في "سنّام" مرتين، كحاملات للقصيدة. "الملك من ثولي" و "سنّام" يمكن قراءتهما كودمان. في "سنّام" يقول المتحدث: ثم يصف الوصف من ثولي وكيف أنه مظلم وحيدًا، يئن من friends grape، ويشاهد عالم مسحوب من színarlor. جميع هذه المناظر يمكن قراءتها في "الملك من ثولي" من جوتفريد، الذي فقد زوجته، وحيدًا، وlost his will to rule أو even live. هي القصيدة وصفًا كما لو كان المتحدث قد دخل إلى قصيدة جوتفريد.

كان جوتفريد كاتبًا مهمًا كان بو يعرفه من أجل لا شيء غير respect for Tennyson. كان بو يقول هذا عن إذا كان يعجبه تنسون. aside من تناوب ذلك إلى تنسون كان بو قد تعرض لعمل جوتفريد في العديد من إعادة النشر التي كانت تجرى بعد النشر الأصلي.

In California law, could a customer injured after slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store be awarded punitive damages by showing the store manager acted with malice because he was informed twice of the spill and failed to have it cleaned for half an hour because he was eating dinner?

A judge is not likely to summarily dismiss Jennifer Palmer’s punitive damage claim. To state a claim that an award of punitive damages is justified, a plaintiff must present evidence that the defendant’s actions were committed with a willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm that would result from the conduct, as well as showing that the conduct was despicable. Palmer will be able to argue that Martin should have known the probable harm of not cleaning a spill because multiple D&D customers were injured from slipping in the months prior to Palmer’s accident, and despite this knowledge, he still failed to have the spill cleaned. Palmer’s argument that Martin’s actions were despicable is less persuasive, but still reasonable given the facts that six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred in 2009 and Martin still failed to take appropriate actions to maintain the safety of his store.

On October 13, 2009 at 5:00 pm, Rich Wayne, an employee of D&D Markets, informed his manager, Paul Martin that there was an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin told Wayne that he was on dinner break and “didn’t have time to deal with customer complaints.” At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan also notified Mr. Martin of the spill, and Martin responded the same way. At 5:30 pm on the thirteenth, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell on the spill and sustained a serious back injury. Prior to Palmer’s accident, five different slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D’s in the year 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are examining whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim.

In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising out of a contract if the defendant acted with “oppression, fraud or malice.” Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct that intended to cause harm, or absent intent, the conduct must be “despicable” and committed with “a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others.” id. at § (c)(1). Courts have characterized conduct as malicious when committed with a conscious disregard of the plaintiff’s rights when the defendant “was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct, and that he willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences.” Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

About four years ago, I took a course on Islam at CBC. One main topic of heated debate in the class was whether or not Islam is a hostile religion. I believe this question is more relevant today than ever. Reflecting on the events since 9/11, I have personally observed that the American media's view of Islam and extremists has shifted from hostile to an extreme form of tolerance. In 2001, I don't think we could have ever elected a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, who had a Muslim background in his family.
The Biography of the Prophet fascinates me because, according to my knowledge of Muhammad's history, the biography contradicts Muhammad's personality. From what I know and have learned in the past, I thought Muhammad coerced converts to Islam. He would conquer tribes and force them to adopt the Islamic religion. However, according to the biography, Muhammad was portrayed as a sort of martyr, misunderstood and even humbled himself to others. After which, people began to see the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out.
There are also uncanny similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' of Muhammad. The most obvious is when he took mutton and milk and multiplied them so that there was enough for forty men. This style of writing makes me believe that the authors wanted Muhammad to be perceived as a humble prophet who needed no proof, but simply lived in truth and miracles. This sort of fallacy is the worst because it downplays the miracle and life of Jesus Christ. To me, it is like they are stealing and trying to take credit for the life and personhood of Jesus through Muhammad.
There are also many stories in the biography that seem to serve an agenda of providing 'witness' or evidence of how people 'on their own' converted to Islam. However, the problem is that many of these stories are at least third-party accounts. That is, the author illustrates that he heard from so-and-so who heard from so-and-so, and so on. I didn't like this as much because, although their intention was to provide proof of the stories' truth, I thought it diminished the stories and made them seem more suspect.
What bothers me the most about this work is that they try to exalt and lift up Muhammad as a godly man who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. However, history contradicts the idea that Muhammad was a gentle and humble man, and I can't help but wonder if Muslims today are aware of the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and his beliefs during his lifetime were immediately left behind as Christian thought developed forward after his life. If we look at this history in broad strokes, we see a trend of Christianity straying farther and farther from its origin. Today’s world shows an ever-growing awareness and an unprecedented progressive tendency. While traditional people remain and will resist any kind of thinking beyond what was taught to them, this portion of the population may not be prominent enough to influence the whole. Among Christians, a historical awareness will grow immensely in future years. A yearning will spread, to distinguish the doctrines that were added into Christianity over time from the actual intent of the religion’s namesake. It may take decades or even centuries, but the outcome will be inevitable: There will be a great reversal in the trend of Christian history. There will be a progression back to its original form. A movement will grow in numbers that will remove layers of doctrine, one after the other, just as if the clock started moving backward, until nothing is left except a conception of what Jesus introduced to humanity on behalf of God, before any other thinkers made such claims. When this trend sweeps through the United States and Europe, influencing masses in its wake to worship as if we were living at the time of Jesus, following only his ideas, the church as an institution will remain strong to lead the way. However, because the theological clock will have moved backward, the extreme proliferation of diversity in Christendom will reverse into more and more uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, between denominations, between divisions of every kind, we will see instead of differences, increasing similarities. Human history is filled with great reversions. Just one example is how Christians were at one time persecuted, shunned and killed by the Roman Empire. But later that empire became a Christian institution. Our country has gone from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversion coming in our future will play itself out in the arena of the Christian religion, undoing history in search of the source, and undoing diversity in the process. It is crucial to note that part of what will make this process possible will be a method of reading Jesus’ words as metaphorical, and not as literal statements. So what is it that happened since Jesus’ lifetime?

If we look far enough back into history, we find only Judaism, the theological beginning for the Christian religion. Monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures, were all at the core of the religion by the time the Romans assumed control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population did not share one spirit. They divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots and a majority of common people.

Upton Sinclair's "The Jungle" illustrates the inherent greed and self-interest of human nature. People are fundamentally self-serving, prioritizing their own wellbeing over others. Sinclair's book exemplifies this through the actions of factory owners and managers who seek to maximize profits at any cost. They disregard any obstacles or harm caused by their operations, including air pollution and waste runoff. The author paints a grim picture of the destructive impact of unchecked capitalism. He shows that even the workers who toil to enrich these owners are treated as disposable, with little regard for their safety or well-being.

The managers and owners prioritize profits above all else, leading to harsh working conditions and arbitrary layoffs. The lack of regulations and protection for workers allowed them to exploit their employees, pushing them to work in unsafe and inhumane conditions. The working conditions in Packingtown were so atrocious that those who worked there were considered little better than slaves. There were no institutions to assist these workers, and the few unions that existed often exploited them further. The workers were trapped in a cycle of exploitation and despair, with no hope of escape.

Many authors employ various techniques to evoke specific feelings or attitudes in their readers about significant subjects. Some techniques are more impactful than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald utilizes a range of these techniques in his novel "The Great Gatsby." Often, he pairs adjectives with nouns that do not normally fit together to create a certain atmosphere around a subject. At other times, he ascribes meaning to symbols and reuses them for the same purpose. Fitzgerald employs this latter technique with numerous colors, including gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In "The Great Gatsby," Fitzgerald imbues these colors with significance, particularly white/gray and red/pink, which he later uses to remind readers of certain feelings associated with important objects.

Fitzgerald associates white/gray with consistency, where white represents elegance and high-class, and gray signifies age and fadedness. He establishes this association at the beginning of the novel with repeated mentions of both colors. Daisy and Jordan are continually "in white" (8), and everyone wears white: Nick wears "white flannels" (41) to Gatsby's party, Tom wears a "white shirt" (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is "powdered milky white" (30). The only time people do not wear white is when Nick first encounters Gatsby's party: "the halls... are gaudy with primary colors" (40). Fitzgerald further reinforces these colors by using them to color common, unimportant subjects: as Nick goes to work, he descends "down the white chasms of lower New York" (56), the names of guests at Gatsby's parties are now "gray names" (61) on Nick's timetable, Catherine's apartment is "one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses" —one of uniformity (28). He also describes ordinary people or places as white or gray: Jordan and Daisy had a "white girlhood" (19), there are "gray cars" and "gray land" (23) in the valley of ashes, the "Italian child" in the train is "gray" (26), and the dog-seller is a "gray old man" (27).

After building sufficient significance around white/gray, Fitzgerald uses them to signify unimportance or uniformity with certain subjects. This use of colors to convey meaning begins with Daisy. After a period with no notable use of these colors, Daisy is described as "dressed in white" in "a little white roadster"; readers start to perceive Daisy as less of a character and more like a uniform addition, something Gatsby desires and yearns for (74). Fitzgerald employs this technique more around Daisy to emphasize her as a more uniform addition, for example, with a "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" (18), and she is again in a "white" (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County is very fertile due to its mild, sunny climate. Common crops include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a strong demand for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms offer tours of their operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This type of operation can allow the landowner to benefit from government programs while improving habitat, thus promoting recreational use and creating opportunities for farm tours and other programs for profit or education. In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, organic farming often results in greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife due to the absence of chemicals. However, organic farming can have higher costs than conventional farming, requiring more intensive labor and management. Losses are often greater, and smaller organic farms lack the scale of efficiency found in large operations. Practices not directly related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife can also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, landowners may seek financial help or expertise to maximize both profits and habitat quality. The chosen land is a 160-acre parcel adjacent to Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, California, featuring chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland near the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan, which currently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals, many of which are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher. Others are declining and may soon be listed, like burrowing owls. This area has been inhabited by Native Americans for countless centuries and was later settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This land was part of an original homestead patent and was likely used for grazing and/or wood production for many decades.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined by what it is not as much as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogeneous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While understanding a culture's generalizations may be appropriate, it is more productive for a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand and how that culture's attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise.

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on "away" territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to "company approved" charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper.

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

The fool hath said in his heart, 'There is no God.' The initial quotation is seen in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm's argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who's is the better of the two, we must, for the sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a god-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.

To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm's passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within oneself to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one's own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn't go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.

This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Some time during the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born who would later be known as Buddha. He renounced the world, attained enlightenment, and his teachings laid the foundation for Buddhism, with Theravada Buddhism being its most traditional sect. The religion has been around for about 2,500 years; it has evolved significantly since Buddha's time. This can be seen particularly in Sri Lanka's Theravada Buddhist community, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Both monks and laypeople participate in this ritual, which has religious significance despite Buddha never having taught about it. These changes range from superficial traditions to the religion's core soteriological principles. Both the monastic and lay Theravada Buddhist communities have had to adapt their doctrinal teachings over time, due to both internal and external influences, both hostile and benign.

To facilitate understanding, several terms will be frequently used. The terms "internal" and "external" refer to forces originating from within the Buddhist community (regardless of monastic status) and from non-Buddhists, respectively. "Hostile" forces are those that harm or intend to harm the Buddhist community, driven by a negative perception of Buddhism. "Benign" forces are those that do not intend to harm or help the Buddhist community, but may do so incidentally.

First, we must examine the core doctrines of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the Triple Gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma encompasses the Tripitaka, the three baskets of Buddhist scriptures. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka includes the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka covers the metaphysics of Buddhism. Key metaphysical concepts include Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence of all things). Recognizing these concepts is essential for escaping Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth. Along with this comes the cessation of lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). The Vinaya Pitaka outlines life rules for both laypeople and monks. Laypeople follow five precepts (I will not kill, I will not lie, I will not steal, I will not commit sexual misconduct, and I will not take intoxicants). Monks follow many more rules. The most fundamental doctrine in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths: life is suffering (Dukkha), attachment causes suffering, suffering can be overcome.

The United States of America and Mexico serve as an example of two nations that, at one time, were embroiled in a protracted rivalry lasting 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p. 145). The high point of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States attacked and defeated Mexico, securing Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Numerous other conflicts occurred between the two nations, ultimately subsiding just before World War I. The rivalry began when Americans and Mexicans clashed over key issues such as religion, culture, and traditions, and had a significant clash of material interests (Schmitt 1974, p. 30-31).

This dynamic is not unique to these two nations; neighboring countries often have rivalries due to shared borders, which can lead to disputes over territories and resources. The United States and Mexico are not alone in this regard. David M. Pletcher (1977) states that "Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41). Indeed, both countries are geographically close to the United States and have been rivals, while other Latin American nations have enjoyed good relations with the United States.

Religious differences were a significant barrier between the two nations, a problem that has affected many nations throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) states that "if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy" (p. 86). Similar to the Cold War's rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union, which was both an ideological struggle and a competition over vital interests, the rivalry between the United States and Mexico was rooted in differing religious preferences. This mistrust was inherited from the historical enmity between the English and Spanish, which posed a significant obstacle to establishing amicable foreign relations.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry period. Most of these disputes involved territorial issues, including border raids from Mexican territory and other frontier problems. Border raids by bandits and outlaws from American towns were a persistent issue until both countries exerted military control over their borders (Schmitt 1974, p. 97).

Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry began to subside as Mexico became increasingly dependent on the United States and finally ended when American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico in the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I suddenly and unexpectedly became disabled due to an illness I had never heard of.

I was a nurse at the time. I chose this profession based on a deep-seated need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick." This mantra echoed in my ears as I grew up. So, even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist, preferably a bit of both, I chose nursing.

However, here I am: 46 years old, single, with no savings and unable to work. To this day, I'm disabled and after fifteen years of living on Social Security Disability, I have nothing left to call my own. Every day is a struggle and an assault on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore, yet there is one thing I know for sure. I could not have gotten through these years without the help of my family and a few good friends. And believe me, when real disaster strikes, you don't feel strong at all.

My point is that life is full of emergencies, big and small. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well one prepares, some things are too big to overcome alone.

I agree that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in the big government's "basket"; it's moldy and falling apart, to be sure. However, I would rather see Americans learn to trust each other again—learning to help one another and to ask for help, rather than each of us individually scrambling for fallout shelters in our backyards.

The Conservatives in the U.S. talk about the "rugged individualism" that built this country; but in truth, what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism, it was compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit, first aid supplies, water purification tablets, plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in case of a biological attack, several flashlights and lots of batteries, lots of candles and waterproof matches, and canned goods. If you have the land and resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food—do it. It's a great idea, as is a wood stove, as long as you don't live in an apartment.

But while you're at it, get to know your neighbors.

Why do organisms evolve in the manner that they do? Are there restrictions or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change? Although, in 1917, D'Arcy Thompson stated that "Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms," the same can be said today. More recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our study is exploring how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic change in Prunum, in combination with experimental studies, can elucidate the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change. We used X-radiographic images of Prunum species to delineate quantitative parameters that could in turn be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were entered into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies that could be used to interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. These results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a structure that travels over time through 360 degrees of space. These revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the central column of the shell and is known as the columella. The speed at which the whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl, referred to as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl of a shell is the last whorl (body whorl). The spire is considered to be all the whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire and the opposite end is referred to as the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed in apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. The usual orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture toward the viewer and with the apex pointing up.

A method for counting whorls is as follows: First, the shell should be viewed from the apical view and then it should be determined where the first suture begins. A line can be drawn dividing the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line, and are estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be viewed as a series of apertures that travel through time and space as the animal accretes its shell. It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is made, it is possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia has remained relatively unchanged over the past decade. Despite the country's progress in meeting many Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation targets, the improvements in child and maternal health have been insufficient to meet the goals by 2015. The reasons for these shortcomings will be discussed below, and they indicate a need to strengthen the entire health system rather than focus on specific programs.

Indonesia has improved the number of births attended by skilled health workers to 72%, but this still includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot provide medical interventions during complicated pregnancies, leading to a high percentage of maternal deaths from hemorrhage. The overall progress in this indicator is somewhat misleading, and there is still much work to be done. Additionally, the percentage of children under five treated for diarrhea by a health professional has decreased, and data on postnatal care is incomplete, indicating a concern in this area with low rates nationwide.

Cesarean-section rates remain below the expected levels at around 4%. The c-section rates further highlight the issue of equity of access, with 7% in urban areas and only 2% in rural areas. This demonstrates that healthcare services are concentrated in urban areas, and there is a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, indicating that the poor find it more difficult to access healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket costs.

When considering the next steps to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the most fundamental question is how to best address the lack of services. Should Indonesia focus on developing specific programmatic approaches or strengthen the overall health system without emphasizing pre and post-pregnancy care for mothers and children? Programmatic approaches are appealing because they have targeted and manageable objectives and generally produce faster results. However, there are drawbacks to consider. Heavy investment in specific areas can lead to reduced funding for other sectors and draw human resources to those areas with more resources. Furthermore, running multiple parallel programs in a single area can result in duplicated, uncoordinated services, leading to increased paperwork for supplies and funding.

Victorian novels are known for their meticulous attention to detail and focus on the aristocracy of the time. However, two novels that deviate from this tradition are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. Both novels incorporate elements of mystery and the odd, which are unusual for the period, thereby enriching the characters and providing insight into their motives and emotions.

“As countless bewildering and confusing ideas flooded into his mind, he found himself still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were arguing furiously. The very words they spoke seemed to echo in his ears; and when he looked at himself, he realized he was talking to them. Suddenly, he jumped back at the sound of gunshots; loud cries and shouts filled the air, lights flashed before his eyes, and chaos reigned as an unseen hand hurriedly carried him away. Throughout these rapid visions, an inexplicable, uneasy awareness of pain tormented him constantly.”

(Charles Dickens, 220)

In both novels, this mystery often manifests through dream sequences or dreamlike states, with varying content and function in each case. In Oliver Twist, these strange events frequently shed light on Oliver's inner turmoil, his personal anguish, and his understanding of the true nature of events around him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in Chapter 28, he relives the incident as if in a dream while struggling to find help. The passage emphasizes Oliver's lack of control over the events transpiring, as well as his dire physical condition, which is reflected in his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself overwhelm him, numbing all his senses, and he doesn't notice the “unseen hand” carrying him away; he experiences his despair again, removed from the shock of pain, as the pain is now constant and intertwined with fear rather than surprise. With Oliver being overwhelmed, the question arises as to whose will brought about his misfortune, for it certainly was not his own. This shooting reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control over anything, unable to attempt to influence the outcome of events even when his life is in danger. A growing sense of defeat in Oliver is also implied, as if Fagin had begun to break him, forcing him into accepting this despair, thereby influencing his ability to react. Otherwise, it can be assumed that Oliver would have made at least some effort, if only for his own life.

“The day passed – day! There was no day; it had come and gone as quickly as it had arrived – and night returned again; night so long and yet so brief; long in its horrifying silence and short in its fleeting hours.”

Two years ago, I worked in an after-school program tutoring elementary-age students. I tried my best to help them with any subject they were struggling in, but my strengths were in English and reading. I was recruited by one of the instructors to help a boy named Adrian, whom I believe was in third or fourth grade, because he was having a lot of trouble reading. It occurred to me that something was wrong; he had the strangest problems. He could pronounce some letters perfectly, but others, not even close. He is of Latino descent, and he spoke perfect English. We struggled until the day I met his mother. I was babysitting a few stragglers while the rest of the after-school group was on a field trip, when his mother walked in. She didn't speak a word of English, only Spanish. With my very basic knowledge of Spanish, we managed to communicate. It was then that I realized: Adrian could read fine; he just didn't know the English alphabet very well. I don't know if this revelation helped him much, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to address the issue of language barriers in schools, especially here in California. I also share it to show that it's not always as obvious as we might think. Even a child who speaks perfect English can still struggle with reading. We all agree this problem exists, so what do we do? In Adrian's case, the solution was fairly simple: tutoring in English reading, particularly the alphabet and pronunciation. But for the many children who barely speak English, the solution is much more complex. There's no one-size-fits-all answer. The key lies in combining various approaches: the dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes. None of these, by itself, will solve the problem.

Firstly, the dual language system is a great idea. Not just for children whose first language is Spanish, but for all children. Studies show that children in two-way bilingual education programs perform better academically. A lot of people are afraid that it's a waste of resources and that most children won't benefit. But that's not true. If we made these programs the norm, rather than the exception, all children would benefit. How can we achieve this? Should we require all teachers to be bilingual? No, that would be unreasonable and unrealistic. However, I believe we can have special aides, tutors, or whatever you want to call them, who are bilingual.

From a young age, we are taught that there is something greater than us, something beyond our comprehension. Some of us learn about it in Sunday school, others in temple, or through self-reflection. Many of us readily accept the religions passed down by our parents, while some reject them outright, denying the existence of anything beyond our personal egocentric universe. We may adopt one set of values only to later change our minds. Regardless of the path we choose, we seek to define our spirituality through our unique perspectives. We search for a guiding light in the darkness to lead us out of the shadows and into the sun.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked him about his favorite bird. We sat on the porch, listening to the rain hitting the tin roof above while we smoked. The gutters carried the rain, drowning the plants along the edge. He looked out into the rain, his gaze a mix of searching and reminiscing. He had lost weight recently, and his clothes hung loosely on him. His hair was thinner, sparser than before. He stared out into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, scared, and unable to talk to my father about how much I'd miss him because acknowledging it would only make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, sat down again, moved my chair closer, and joined him in watching the rain fall on the June twilight.

My father passed away in December of that year, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemotherapy and radiation had not relieved his suffering, but kept him alive a few more months than the doctors had predicted. I couldn't understand the purpose of it; what benefit was there in prolonging his suffering? In the quiet of the night, I didn't say any prayers. If God existed, he had stopped listening to me long ago.

I hadn't wanted to watch him pass from this life into the next. So I hadn't. I couldn't stand to watch the life that created me as it ended. I wanted to remember my father by how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew him better than anyone, better than his family did, and knew he wouldn't want his only child to be a witness to his death. I curled up in my bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one even called me.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is, in essence and in name, a "oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" as Ian Watt describes in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic mode has been both disparaged and praised, accused of having no real depth, and lauded for the 'terrible sublime' aspect it seemed to evoke (Burke). The original "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, combined "the ancient and the modern" romances to create the proto-Gothic genre and a new form of literary expression. Walpole used "old" theatrical elements and 'new' mimicry of nature in 'modern' novels to present what he termed "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre draws heavily on medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. When The Castle of Otranto was published, the term "gothic" was used to describe various peoples, styles, and time periods, often viewed as archaic or unsophisticated despite "modern" societal and literary advancements. The blend of theatrical "Gothic" elements and the new novel format, allowing readers a more personal view of character psychology, is what has allowed Gothic literature to endure and seem both obsolete and new to readers displaced in time from its origins.

One of the most significant themes in Gothic novels is the concept of Chivalry. The medieval idea of chivalry, the process of training a proper knight, is both retained and transformed in Walpole's The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is important to Gothic writers because it represents the classic knight: brave, honorable, and competent. They saw this ideal lacking in contemporary society. Through chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" is idealized and romanticized, hinting at the future evolution of Gothic to Romantic literature, and is used to try to improve the present. Walpole was writing during a politically troubled time and was despairing over the future. He may have begun to feel, though not explicitly, that the morality and innate "goodness" of the Gothic era had been lost in the present society. This is evident in several characters, with Frederic being one example. The reader can sense before meeting Frederic that he embodies many chivalric traits. He is described as:

Frederic is foremost a prince, has suffered much, been suitably affected by tragedy, and is currently supposed to have been killed by infidels. The figure of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is exaggerated, introducing the soon-to-be Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management refers to the process of moving goods from the customer order through the raw materials stage, supply, production, and distribution to the customer. The term was coined in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver. Keith Oliver described the overall process of planning, implementing, and controlling what happens in the supply chain to meet customers' needs quickly and efficiently. There are six key elements in a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Managers use these six key elements to provide the best customer service. Production is the first step in the supply chain process. Production is the foundation for the entire supply chain process. The production stage determines the timing, reason, location, and method of production. Managers need to know what customers want in order to make informed decisions. To determine what customers want, managers can observe the market. The market is the biggest indicator of what customers demand. Once managers analyze the market and understand customer demand, they can decide which products to produce and in what quantities. After deciding on what to produce and in what quantities, managers must determine where to produce the products and choose the best facility for volume and quality, keeping in mind customer demand and satisfaction. Once the production location is determined, the next step is for managers to focus on workload scheduling and equipment maintenance. Production is a critical step in the supply chain process. Every detail is crucial throughout the process. If any detail is not planned properly, it could cost the company significant time and money in the long run. For example, I used to work at Wal-Mart and Target retail stores. Both companies have designed processes for every aspect of the business, including how an employee's uniform should look and how shipments are received from trucks. Having outlined processes allows a company to operate smoothly without confusion about direction and expectations. The second key element in supply chain management is supply. Supply involves strategic decisions to determine the core capabilities of a facility and how outsourcing partnerships should be developed from these decisions. A company may have multiple production divisions for a single product, each with different equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager must decide which division is the best fit for the different processes of the product. Managers may also choose to outsource work to other companies. The core reason managers would outsource work is to increase velocity. Velocity refers to the ability to provide quality and flexibility while simultaneously reducing costs or maintaining low cost levels.

Hitler is alive in Myanmar, the sign says.

Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner with a piece of cardboard held above her head, the unsettling message scrawled with Sharpie on her sign. Myanmar, also known as Burma, is a Southeast Asian country ruled by a tyrannical military junta who seized power in 1962 through a coup d’état. In 2007, a number of street protests occurred, the first public protests in a decade. Led by a large number of Burmese monks, these protests were dubbed "The Saffron Revolution," named after the color of the robes that the monks wore. After the initial uprisings, the general public became interested in the protests, and while the Burmese government begrudgingly allowed the monks to engage in peaceful gatherings, violence soon escalated into what some considered an all-out war between the monks and the military junta. The military actively invaded and ransacked monasteries around the country. Foreign journalists were rounded up and imprisoned on sight, with a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai killed on September 27th, 2007, simply for being present at a street protest. While the official death toll stood at 13 killed, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army some days prior to the official report, is quoted as having said, “Many more people have been killed in recent days than you’ve heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand.”

This is nothing new. While these are some of the most recent examples of atrocities taking place in our world, a government’s desire to quash dissent and maintain complete rule over its citizenry has been around for as long as civilization itself. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to have complete executive ruling over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are believed to actually be gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through the invention of Motorola cell phones and hara-kiri, and our current president, George W. Bush, has weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary group of the Republican Party.

Some of the most well-known examples of these actions are such incidents as the 1989 June 4th Tiananmen Square protest, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students all gathered to protest the authoritarian rule of the government. The death toll in that particular instance ranges widely, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead to reports let out by the Chinese Red Cross, declaring between 2,000-3,000 dead. Another is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began a systematic killing of all Tutsis, as well as political moderates, irrespective of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler’s ‘Third Reich’, a period spanning several years and several countries where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington's jazz legacy is largely due to his longevity and the creative power he brought to shaping his orchestra. Ellington's piano presence in many pieces is subtle, but as a composer, he excelled at creating rich and intricate compositions that highlighted the individual talents of the band members. He provided a structure where soloists could freely improvise and wrote tightly orchestrated pieces that showcased each member's unique style. By doing this, he also emphasized the overall tone of the orchestra, creating coherent and original sounds tailored to each piece. Ellington's mastery of individual players' sounds and their integration into the ensemble allowed him to compose some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history. The Grove Music dictionary mentions "Creole Love Call" as an example of how Ellington used the voice as an instrument throughout his career. This early piece showcases his ability to add texture and color without lyrics and complement soloists' styles. "Creole Love Call" is a slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues with six choruses: Chorus 1: Voice and reed call and response, starting smooth then rough. Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo elaborates the melody and emphasizes blue notes. Chorus 3: High-register clarinet solo backed by subtle syncopated piano. Chorus 4: The band mimics the first chorus with brass and reed call and response. Chorus 5: Climactic chorus with reeds in high register and syncopated stop time from brass and rhythm. Chorus 6: Returns to the first chorus structure with voice growling as an instrument. A vocal run and dissonant trombone finish. Ellington's use of voice for tone color is a recurring theme in his work. In "Hot and Bothered," a year later, Ellington combines tight orchestration with tone color. A call and response between Bubber Miley's muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing uses Miley's vocal elements and Cox's instrumental voice. "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)" extends these ideas, with Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton introducing the melody on muted trombone.

She had always felt like she needed something, a desire that couldn't be fulfilled. It began when she was about 14, entering adolescence. Even three years later, at 17, the feeling remained. She had decided she wanted someone rather than a thing, but she found no interest in any boys. Some were drawn to her, tried to woo her, but none appealed to her. She often questioned this, wondering what could cause such a situation. After years of contemplation, she had formed theories but nothing conclusive. So she lived her life, continually questioning her desires.

At home, a typical day was peaceful. Her parents were kind and calm, rarely arguing with each other or with her. They argued only about her independence and free spirit. Despite her parents' calm demeanor, she was bold and lively, making her very likable. However, today was not peaceful. As she moved from room to room seeking inspiration, she heard a scream from the kitchen. She rushed in to find her mother lying on the ground, groaning in pain. Her daughter ran to her side, asking, "Mom? Mom, what's wrong?" Her mother, in distress, said, "Ow... sweetie, please... take me to the hospital." Her daughter, knowing her mother was in immense pain, quickly helped her to the car. She drove her to the hospital, seeking medical attention.

At the hospital, the smell of disinfectant and sickness filled the air, but her daughter was focused on helping her mother. She carried her mother quickly to the doctors, who rushed to her aid. It turned out her mother had fallen from a step stool trying to reach a high shelf.

This study aimed to demonstrate that adherence to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), as indicated by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is linked to a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke mortality. The aMed diet, a modified version of the Med diet, is characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains and legumes), monounsaturated fats (compared to saturated fats) and fish, and lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol intake is permitted.

Previous prospective studies have shown an inverse association between adherence to the Med diet and the risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, and a clinical trial demonstrated that the Med diet is more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and lowering the total-to-high-density lipoprotein cholesterol ratio in overweight individuals. However, prior studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study tracked 74,886 women aged 38 to 63 without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Over six periods from 1984 to 2004, the researchers calculated an aMed diet score based on self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake over the preceding year. Over 95% of the nurses maintained their participation throughout the 20-year period. The FFQs underwent validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed by reviewing medical or hospital records, autopsy reports, or death certificates. Where records were unavailable, cases were classified as “probable” and included, with about 17% of strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To minimize random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were computed (by averaging scores from two prior years). Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse the results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to examine the association between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Enhanced adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. Over 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were identified. Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America faced a catastrophic financial crisis. Unemployment surged, the real estate market crashed, and many of America's largest and most important corporations were devastated. This recession is ongoing, so we must ask: How did this crisis occur, and how can we prevent it in the future? Essentially, the financial crisis was the result of selfish and naive political decision-making that pressured banks and firms to issue subprime loans to an immature and inadequate financial infrastructure. Simultaneously, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to guarantee and repack these mortgages into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserves and transferred this chaos to the repacked mortgages they had sold, and to the wider economy.

The seeds of the financial crisis were sown in 1999 during the Clinton administration, as the president sought re-election by building his popularity. To achieve this, the Clinton administration eased lending restrictions, setting the stage for the subprime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's largest mortgage underwriter, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans to low and moderate-income individuals and felt pressure from shareholders to maintain its phenomenal profit growth.” Holmes correctly forecast the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may face trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, imprudent lending would indeed lead to the economy's collapse.

Numerous factors contributed to the economic downturn, one of which was the complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were widely used in the years leading up to the crisis, further intertwining the economy with the housing market. This caused U.S. households and financial markets to become heavily reliant on the housing market, making them extremely vulnerable to even slight price changes.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were severely impacted. The top five U.S. investment banks together reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the U.S. GDP. In the end, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at a discount, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subject to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were placed under government control in September 2008.
