Ah, exposition.  That part of your story where you spread your wings and soar, captivating everyone with your magnetic, magical prose.  Or the part where your readers nod off or hit the "Back" button while swearing at your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself stuck in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even the good kind.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing rule, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into passages where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder, whispering to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil on the other shoulder urging you to tell your audience every little detail of each character's childhood).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information like "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author is doing the telling.

Here's an example.  As you're reading a story, you're told that the heroine met her beloved at this place and time, they were married in a grand fashion, and her husband was murdered in front of her.  You wouldn't expect this entire sequence to take two pages, with both of them having only two lines of dialogue each.  You'd expect the author to spend time on the husband's character, showing through his words and actions how deeply he loves his wife, and you'd expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how his presence changed and enriched her life (especially if the story later states this outright).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would make you emotionally invested in his fate and give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through his eyes, and so on.  You'd mourn his death with her and become more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you'd expect substance to the storyline's skeleton: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that substance.  (*looks at the metaphor, sighs, presses on*)  It's sometimes tempting to rush through certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, now works as a gas station night manager, has been married twice, no kids, likes to fish on weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one, which was live, was from NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man named Shad Hostettler from Ashley, Ohio who stabbed his wife. They didn't mention her name, but showed his mug shot. He looked like a bad person. They devoted about two minutes to this story as it was still developing. The only details given were that he stabbed her multiple times and was arrested. I think they gave this story an appropriate amount of time.

The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, an 18-year-old. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and was critically injured; no one was arrested, and there were no suspects yet. The SWAT team was investigating. This story seemed short, and I believe this might be because it involved a "black" man or a black neighborhood. I've noticed (and for years) that minorities are often ignored when they are crime victims. If a white kid or adult is missing or a crime victim, the media goes crazy; but if it's a minority, they're lucky if it's even mentioned.

The next story was about a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where it might have happened. They determined it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers are offering a $5,000 reward for information leading to the shooter's arrest.

The next story was about predicted rain and thunderstorms for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would stay in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The story was a bit short, but they wanted to use it as a teaser to keep you watching.

They also reported a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said the robber was a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. He was about six feet tall and weighed about 150 pounds. They seemed to emphasize his race and the darkness of his skin. I thought they spent an unusual amount of time on this.

Another story was about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin. He was convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana from Texas to Ohio in large amounts. One thing I noticed was that they said he was sentenced to "300" months instead of "twenty-five years." I don't know why they did that, whether they thought it sounded harsher or what. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, which didn't seem relevant to the story.

There is a bond between brothers, an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie various emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, among others. Brothers understand each other more than anyone else with a similar bond, and they can only see themselves reflected in their brother. It is in the most dire situations that this bond truly shines, whether it is for good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they come with a great cost. Understanding the emotions born from this fraternal connection means accepting the consequences they bring. When one can look into a brother's eyes and see their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. Their true character is revealed in their actions and the consequences of those actions. In “The Scarlet Ibis,” two brothers explore this theme and the accompanying raging emotions. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys embark on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through the direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator's point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are significant influences on his actions.

The protagonist’s actions can be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had yearned for a brother he could teach all his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously, these things were impossible given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making it unlikely he would even survive. Even so, it was almost impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, whose head was filled with wild fantasies, to have all those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he even contemplated killing Doodle by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart softened when Doodle smiled at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist hope! This shows that his conviction was probably not very strong. Deep down, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complex, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also evolved. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.

Information processing begins with input from the sensory organs, which convert physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing combines very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.

Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.

In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.

There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley critiques the looming threat posed by both technology and the capitalist system that reinforces it, portraying a dystopian future in his novel Brave New World. People here prioritize collective harmony over individuality and are conditioned from youth to seek instant happiness above all else. The citizens are mere pawns in a game dictated by the World Controller, highlighting Huxley's Marxist critique of these systems. Terms like homogenization and reification reinforce his commentary on the flaws of the emerging economy.

Capitalism is satirized through the Marxist concept of false consciousness, which prevents the common people from understanding their true economic relations. The ruling class maintains control over the proletariat and common laborers, conditioning them to focus on personal gain. In Brave New World, lower classes like Delta and Gamma have no independent will; through hypnopædia, they are instilled with a strong desire to consume and indulge, manipulated by the World Controller. Hegemony, or the dominance of a ruling class, is evident here, with lower classes unaware of their manipulation. Upper classes, though aware, rarely challenge this; few Alphas or Betas like Bernard actively resist their roles.

In Brave New World, relationships between individuals lack depth, with characters, even major ones, being indistinct. Huxley seems to imply that technology and capitalism strip people of free will and expression. Love and intense emotions are absent; interactions are superficial, focusing on physical appearances. Each class accepts its place in the hierarchy, reflecting the socioeconomic effects of capitalism. Their loyalty to their role within the community mirrors Marxist views of the proletariat, who are deluded into believing their own superiority as long as they consume and obey.

I have been studying at University Park for approximately two and a half years, which is roughly four and a half semesters. Many students, including myself, find navigating the campus challenging. In my freshman year, I was housed in an East Halls dorm, the farthest eastward location on campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from my residence in Stuart Hall to classes in distant locations like the Willard Building, near the campus center, could take up to 25 minutes, especially in bad weather, which is frequent in State College. Speaking with an alumni who is only slightly older than me, I learned that not long ago, the East Halls dorms were isolated by vast tracts of unused land. Now, that empty space has been developed into sports fields, new buildings including the new Creamery and health services building, and surrounded by apartments. As the campus continues to expand, traveling from one point to another becomes increasingly difficult. What is the most effective solution to this mobility issue? On a college campus, the bicycle is the best option. However, simply having bikes won't solve the problem; students need to use them, and the campus must be designed to accommodate them.

I recently discussed this with a friend who had resumed cycling after a few years. He mentioned that he wondered why he had stopped in the first place. "Bikes are great," he said, "for a few years it wasn't fashionable to ride bikes, but it's the only reliable way to get around." In addition to being good for your health, cycling is the most efficient mode of transportation. A bowl of oatmeal and a bit of exercise can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus, as far from the center as some dorms. The smartest decision I made this year was to buy a bike. My daily class at Thomas Building is about a 25-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can reduce that to just 5 minutes, if I pedal fast enough. However, Pollock Road, the direct route to Thomas Building from my house, is not always easy to navigate, whether by bike or on foot. While walking also has its advantages, I'm too busy to walk. If I didn't have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option to get to class. Walking to Thomas every day would add an extra 30-40 minutes to my day, which is about 2.5 hours a week. Adding the time needed for walking to and from other classes, appointments, etc., it would consume more time than I can afford to spare.
